description:
Former FBI Agent Reveals the Hidden Behaviours That Expose Lies, Build Power & Win Negotiations. 

Joe Navarro spent 25 years in the FBI catching spies and decoding human behavior. In this episode, he shares the powerful secrets of body language, psychological influence, and negotiation mastery that the government uses—but most people never learn.

From spotting deception in a single glance to taking control of a room without saying a word, Joe breaks down the nonverbal cues that shape every interaction in your life.

You’ll learn:
- How to detect lies in seconds
- The body language signals that scream insecurity
- FBI techniques for dominating negotiations
- Why first impressions are formed in under 3 milliseconds
- How to train confidence like a muscle
- And the subtle signals you’re unknowingly sending right now

Plus, Joe shares real spy stories, including the tiny mistake that gave one away—and how posture, eye contact, and even how you carry flowers can reveal everything.

comments.text:
Wow – what an incredible mix of love, curiosity, and even grammar lessons in here 😅
First off, to all of you who took the time to like, subscribe, or even just drop a thoughtful comment – thank you deeply. You’re the reason I keep doing this. 🙏🏾

To my new friends in New Zealand 🇳🇿, to those diving deep into language debates 🇬🇧📚, and to the ones hunting for Joe’s YouTube channel –
👉 You’re seen, you’re heard, and yes, you’re appreciated.

Re: the whole “Me and my team” vs “My team and I” –
You’re absolutely right, technically it should be “My team and I”…
But hey, I guess in that moment my passion got ahead of my grammar 😅
Sometimes Me and my team just feels more real, you know?

Lastly – to whoever asked “Who has time for all this?”
…Maybe the people who realize the value of learning from one of the greatest behavioral minds of our time 🧠✨

Thanks again, legends. Let’s keep growing, questioning, and connecting 🖤

comments.text: I'm just going into this, with a some worry. A number of neurological mishaps and conditions can vastly alter what your face is 'saying'. Often, this is not immediately obvious. It can work both ways and facial recognition can be poor also. Specialist Neurologists often wear something unique to their sessions to help. Picking one distinct feature or saying you are a little deaf are workarounds, as people are rushed. Across the population, a sudden tummy cramp, random worry, etc, etc, can register as an 'unknown' on facial expression. Do not take every facial muscle as indicative without COMMUNICATION. Guilt is a bad one, people transfer guilt to obtain punishment, over cover it for other reasons, confessing to things they did not do. The Human brain is akin to a mini universe, and part of the universe. Remember, please: People are COMPLICATED.
